@shakuzen You are right, Feign or directly using RestTemplate are the alternatives. I know how to do it. The problem is which is the best solution or the most effective way. User will still need model Span or Trace as entity in this case.

Maybe we can wait for few days if there are other users want the same feature before we close it.
I still believe its would be valuable to have such features. Zipkin GUI is not enough as an output for the whole distributed tracing solution.

here's a working example, where the only dependencies are io.github.openfeign:feign-core and io.zipkin.zipkin2:zipkin

Hopefully this can buy you time as we don't typically enter work like creating a new library etc within days anyway.

```java

  interface Zipkin {

    @RequestLine("GET /api/v2/trace/{traceId}")
    List<Span> getTrace(@Param("traceId") String traceId);

    static Zipkin connect() {
      Decoder decoder = new Decoder.Default() {
        @Override
        public Object decode(Response response, Type type) throws IOException {
          if (response.request().url().contains("/api/v2/trace/")) {
            byte[] bytes = (byte[]) super.decode(response, byte[].class);
            if (bytes == null) return null;
            return SpanBytesDecoder.JSON_V2.decodeList(bytes);
          }
          return super.decode(response, type);
        }
      };

      return Feign.builder()
          .decoder(decoder)
          .logger(new Logger.ErrorLogger())
          .logLevel(Logger.Level.BASIC)
          .target(Zipkin.class, "http://localhost:9411");
    }
  }

  public static void main(String... args) {
    Zipkin zipkin = Zipkin.connect();

    System.out.println(zipkin.getTrace("96e7c98dd2d01b3c"));
  }
```

the root client span is stand-alone-service.. if you click on the first
span you should see it in the details. the name chosen on the left is based
on servers. if you go to the dependency graph you should see
stand-alone-service.

